library(psych)
describe(bankruptcy)
## Histogram
bankruptcy_counts <- bankruptcy %>%
  group_by(`Bankrupt?`) %>%
  summarise(Count = n()) %>%
  mutate(Percent = Count / sum(Count) * 100)

# Now create the plot
ggplot(bankruptcy_counts, aes(x = factor(`Bankrupt?`), y = Count, fill = factor(`Bankrupt?`))) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  geom_text(aes(label = sprintf("%.2f%%", Percent)), 
            position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5), 
            color = "white", size = 3.5) +
  labs(title = "Barplot of Bankruptcy", x = "Bankruptcy", y = "Frequency") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("blue", "orange"), 
                    labels = c("Not Bankrupt", "Bankrupt")) +
  theme_minimal()

# imbalance dataset, only 3.23% of bankrupt data is recorded
options(repr.plot.width = 6, repr.plot.height = 3) # Resize plot option

bankruptcy |>
  ggplot(aes(x = `ROA(C) before interest and depreciation before interest`)) +
  geom_histogram(alpha = 0.7, bins = 40, fill = "blue") +
  theme_bw() +
  scale_x_continuous(labels = scales::comma) +
  labs(title = "Histogram of ROA (Return on Assets)",
       x = "ROA (Return on Assets)",
       y = "Frequency")

The histogram exhibits a distribution of Return on Assets (ROA) with a modal peak marginally below the 0.5 threshold, indicating a median ROA value for the sampled entities that is somewhat less than 50 percent. The data demonstrates a concentration of ROA metrics predominantly within the interquartile range of 0.25 to 0.75, denoting a moderate dispersion around the central tendency of the dataset. Notably, the distribution is characterized by a negative skewness, suggesting a preponderance of firms with ROA figures that are lower than the mode, potentially indicative of suboptimal asset performance across the cohort.

The histogram also evidences elongated tails on both extremities of the ROA spectrum, alluding to the existence of statistical outliers. Such outliers may correspond to enterprises with atypically elevated profitability ratios or those possibly experiencing substantial fiscal distress. The presence of such extreme values may necessitate further investigation to ascertain their influence on the overall analysis and potential implications for financial robustness and risk of insolvency.

## Model using LightGBM
## Splitting data
# Splitting the data into training and test sets 
bankruptcy_train <- Bankrupt?[1:4773, ] # 70% of 6819 for training
bankruptcy_test <- Bankrupt?[4774:nrow(bankruptcy), ] # remaining 30% for testing

Splitting dataset into 70% for trainning and 30% for test set.

First Model Training Setting up parameters to train

train_params <- list(objective = "binary", # Loss function
                     boosting_type = "gbdt",
                     boost_from_average = "false",
                     learning_rate = 0.005, # Learning rate
                     num_leaves = 192, # Max nb leaves in tree
                     min_gain_to_split = 0,
                     feature_fraction = 0.3, # % of features
                     bagging_freq = 1,
                     bagging_fraction = 0.7, # % of observations
                     min_data_in_leaf = 100,
                     lambda_l1 = 0,
                     lambda_l2 = 0)
data_matrix <- as.matrix(bankruptcy_train |> select(-`Bankrupt?`))

# Train LightGBM model
bst_k <- lightgbm(
  data = data_matrix,
  label = bankruptcy_train$`Bankrupt?`, # Target / label
  params = train_params,        # Passing parameter values
  nrounds = 2000,     # Number of boosting rounds
  eval_freq = 20,  # Evaluate the model every 20 rounds
  verbose = -1  # Disable verbose output
)
# Making predictions
predict(bst_k, bankruptcy_test[1:1000,] |> select(-`Bankrupt?`) |> as.matrix()) |> round() |> head(9)

This defines the models parameters to guide how it learns from the data, such as using a specific algorithm (GBDT), a slow learning rate, and controls to prevent overfitting (like limiting the number of features and data used in each iteration). The training data is prepared by excluding the target variable (Bankrupt?). The model is then trained on this data for 2000 iterations, with its performance evaluated every 20 rounds.

Second Model Trainning Attempt

## 2nd Model Training Attempt
### Updated of the Trainning parameters

nb_feat <- ncol(bankruptcy_train |> select(-`Bankrupt?`)) # Nb features
mono_const <- rep(0, nb_feat)
mono_const[1] <- 1             # First feature is amount: fraud increases with amount

train_params <- list(
  num_leaves = 15,           # Max nb leaves in tree
  learning_rate = 0.1,       # Learning rate
  objective = "binary",      # Loss function
  max_depth = 4,             # Max depth of trees
  min_data_in_leaf = 50,     # Nb points in leaf
  bagging_fraction = 0.5,    # % of observations
  feature_fraction = 0.7,    # % of features
  nthread = 4,               # Parallelization
  boosting = "dart",         # DART = dropping
  drop_rate = 0.1,           # Dropping rate
  lambda_l1 = 0.3,           # Penalizing leave norms
  seed = 42,                 # For reproducibility?
  # early stopping not available with DARTs
  #early_stopping_round = 10, # Early stopping after X round if no improvement
  monotone_constraints = mono_const,
  force_row_wise = T
)

## Training the model
bst <- lightgbm(
  data = bankruptcy_train |> select(-`Bankrupt?`) |> as.matrix(),
  label = bankruptcy_train$`Bankrupt?`, # Target / label
  params = train_params,        # Passing parameter values
  nrounds = 1000,
  eval_freq = 20, 
  verbose = -1
)
### Cross Validation
cv_model <- lgb.cv(
  params = train_params,
  data = bankruptcy_train |> select(-`Bankrupt?`) |> as.matrix(),
  label = bankruptcy_train$`Bankrupt?` # Target / label
)
cv_model$record_evals
### Hyper Tuning of the parameters
num_leaves <- c(5,30)
learning_rate <- c(0.01, 0.05, 0.2)
pars <- expand.grid(num_leaves, learning_rate)
num_leaves <- pars[,1]
learning_rate <- pars[,2]
train_func <- function(num_leaves, learning_rate, bankruptcy_train){
  train_params <- list(             # First, the list of params
    num_leaves = num_leaves,        # Max nb leaves in tree
    learning_rate = learning_rate,  # Learning rate
    objective = "binary",           # Loss function
    max_depth = 3,                  # Max depth of trees
    min_data_in_leaf = 50,          # Nb points in leaf
    bagging_fraction = 0.5,         # % of observations
    feature_fraction = 0.7,         # % of features
    nthread = 4,                    # Parallelization
    force_row_wise = T
  )
  # Next we train
  bst <- lightgbm(
    data = bankruptcy_train |> select(-`Bankrupt?`) |> as.matrix(),
    label = bankruptcy_train$`Bankrupt?`, # Target / label
    params = train_params,        # Passing parameter values
    eval_freq = 50,
    nrounds = 1000,
    verbose = -1
  )
  # Next, we record the final loss (depends on the model/loss defined above)
  return(loss = bst$record_evals$train$binary_logloss$eval[[10]]) 
}
train_func(10, 0.1, bankruptcy_train) # Testing
grd <- pmap(list(num_leaves, learning_rate),     # Parameters for the grid search
            train_func,                          # Function on which to apply the grid search
            bankruptcy_train = bankruptcy_train            # Non-changing argument (data is fixed)
)
grd <- bind_cols(pars, tibble(loss = grd))
preds <- predict(bst, bankruptcy_test[1:700,] |> 
                   select(-`Bankrupt?`) |>
                   data.matrix()) |>
  round()
print(preds |> head(9))
